@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}Introduction@{uu}@{ub}@{par}

AG2HH is a tool to convert standard @{amigaguide} documents into Maxon's
HotHelp format.@{par}

It does @{b}not @{ub}only create simple header files like Maxon's EasyHotHelp does,
instead it really converts the whole text! This gives you the ability to
edit the final output and add some special HotHelp features, eg. graphics or
something.@{par}

AG2HH is @{b}VERY @{ub}fast! On my machine (A1200/030/50) it converts the GoldED
4.7.2 manual (358742 bytes) in 14.876 seconds, which is an overall speed of
477 lines/s or 24115 bytes/s.@{par}

Note that you also need the HotHelpComp compiler. This will not be provided
within this archive.@{par}


@{lindent 2}  @{b}@{u}68020+ versions@{uu}@{ub}@{lindent 0}@{par}

Please do @{b}not @{ub}ask for special compiled versions for 68020+ CPUs!@{par}

Whenever a new version is finished I do some Benchmark tests on my machine.
In version 2.4, a 68020 version gives a speed gain of ~1.237% on my
computer, that is only ~0.538 seconds per MByte!@{par}
(Also tested with the GoldED 4.7.2 manual.)@{par}

@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}Usage@{uu}@{ub}@{par}

AG2HH can only be used from the Shell:@{par}

@{lindent 8}  @{i}AG2HH <input file> <output file> [-p <preferences file>] [-a] [-ak] [-as]
[-m] [-im] [-np] [-nw] [-q] @{ui}@{lindent 0}@{par}

AG2HH will take the input file in @{amigaguide} format and creates the output
file in Maxon's HotHelp format. If the output file already exists, it will
be overwritten without @{"warnings" link "Warnings"}.@{par}


@{b}Parameters: @{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 5}@{i}-p   @{ui}Specify the path to a standard HotHelpCompiler.Pref file as created by
HotHelpComp.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 5}@{i}-a   @{ui}Switch AutoDoc mode on. Whenever a reference contains a pair of
brackets ("@{fg highlight}()@{fg text}") at its end, these brackets will, of course, be
stripped. If you switch AutoDoc mode on, AG2HH will output "@{fg highlight}()@{fg text}" right
behind the reference. For example, "@{fg highlight}\@{" test() " link ...}@{fg text}" would
become "@{fg highlight}|QV|test|QV|()@{fg text}" instead of only "@{fg highlight}|QV|test|QV|@{fg text}".@{par}

However, if the link contains a "@{fg highlight}/@{fg text}" character, only the last part of
the link will be converted into a reference. For example,
"@{fg highlight}\@{"exec.library/AllocVec()" link ...}@{fg text}" would become
"@{fg highlight}exec.library/|QV|AllocVec|QV|()@{fg text}" instead of
"@{fg highlight}|QV|exec.library/AllocVec|QV|()@{fg text}". This behaviour is new in version
2.2.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 5}@{i}-ak  @{ui}Switch AutoKeysÛ mode on. See below for details.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 5}@{i}-as  @{ui}Switch AutoSpacesÛ mode on. Whenever a references contains leading
and/or trailing spaces, these spaces will be put before/after the final
reference. This gives a better look to most converted documents. For
example, "@{fg highlight}\@{"  foo  " link bar}@{fg text}" will become "@{fg highlight}  |QV|foo|QV|  @{fg text}" instead
of only "@{fg highlight}|QV|foo|QV|@{fg text}".@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 5}@{i}-m   @{ui}Switch MUI mode on. See below for details.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 5}@{i}-im  @{ui}Switch image mode on. This mode is used to convert PowerGuide "@{fg highlight}\@image@{fg text}"
commands into corresponding "@{fg highlight}|GRAF|<filename>@{fg text}" commands.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 5}@{i}-np  @{ui}Suppress progress display only.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 5}@{i}-nw  @{ui}Suppress warnings only.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 5}@{i}-q   @{ui}Suppress all visual output.@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{b}Example invocations:@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 2}- Convert; use user preferences:@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 10}    @{i}AG2HH MyProject.guide MyProject.txt -p Prefs/HotHelpCompiler.Pref @{ui}@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 2}- Convert; use standard codes, AutoDoc mode, no progress display:@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 10}    @{i}AG2HH MyProject.guide MyProject.txt -a -np @{ui}@{lindent 0}@{par}



@{lindent 2}  @{b}@{u}AutoKeysÛ mode@{uu}@{ub}@{lindent 0}@{par}

As you might know from the original @{amigaguide} system, you can create links
with totally different labels than their referenced nodes.@{par}

For example, you can link a button with the label "foo" to the node "bar".
A second button named "foobar" could also be linked to the node "bar".@{par}

In HotHelp, this is not possible. Kinda stupid, huh? Who knows why...@{par}

This is where AG2HH's AutoKeysÛ mode can help. It creates invisible keys
inside the destination entries. In the above example, it would not only
create the key "bar" as usual, but also "foo" and "foobar".@{par}

You should always use the -ak parameter to get the best results.@{par}

Note that using the -ak parameter needs two passes to process the input
file.@{par}


@{lindent 2}  @{b}@{u}MUI mode@{uu} @{ub}@{lindent 0}@{par}

When you use the original AD2AG utility to convert autodocs into @{amigaguide}
documents, you will notice some problems with the MUI docs. The best way to
convert them is to let AD2AG create brackets ("@{fg highlight}()@{fg text}") behind every method
name, attribute name and so on.@{par}

Furthermore, you surely want to use the AutoDoc mode since these are
autodocs and there might be some normal links to normal functions.
Unfortunately, you will also get the bracket pairs behind every method name,
attributes and all that stuff!@{par}

The new MUI mode since AG2HH 2.2 brings the solution. If the first 5
characters of a reference label are one of the following:@{par}

@{tab}MUIA_@{tab}@{tab}MUIO_@{par}
@{tab}MUIC_@{tab}@{tab}MUIP_@{par}
@{tab}MUIE_@{tab}@{tab}MUIS_@{par}
@{tab}MUII_@{tab}@{tab}MUIV_@{par}
@{tab}MUIM_@{tab}@{tab}MUIX_@{par}

the normal brackets will be omitted, even when using the AutoDoc mode!@{par}


@{lindent 2}  @{b}@{u}Notes on usage@{uu}@{ub}@{lindent 0}@{par}

Most errors during compilation of converted documents only show up because
of misunderstandings by HotHelpComp.@{par}

For example, if a converted document contains the text "@{fg highlight}|QV|GT|QV|@{fg text}", one
would assume a reference to the entry "@{fg highlight}GT@{fg text}". Unfortunately, HotHelpComp fails
to compile the source code because it finds a "@{fg highlight}|GT|@{fg text}" for some reason, which
is a command like "@{fg highlight}|QV|@{fg text}".@{par}

Because of those stupid bugs in HotHelpComp, it is really important that you
use custom settings that can never ever interfer with HotHelpComp's
assumptions!@{par}

In the AG2HH archive you will find a preferences file for HotHelpComp. I
used the syntax "@{fg highlight}<<<@{b}@{fg fill}COMMAND@{fg highlight}@{ub}>>>@{fg text}" in it. You will hopefully never find any
@{amigaguide} documents using such weird texts...@{par}

@endnode
@node "Commands" "Commands"
@{par}
  @{lindent 2}@{b}@{u}General information@{uu} @{ub}@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{fg highlight}Note that this section only uses the default preferences as they are shipped
together with the HotHelp system from Maxon. You can always set your own
@{"preferences" link "Preferences"} by using the -p @{"parameter" link "Usage"}.@{fg text}@{par}

All entry names and reference labels will be cut down to the maximum size of
49 characters. Additionally, the illegal characters "@{fg highlight}?%#|()[]\\*@{b}@{fg fill}<TAB>@{fg text}@{ub}" (not
including the first and last quote) will be filtered out (for autodocs, have
a look at the -a parameter). Furthermore, all leading and trailing
whitespaces must be filtered out, eg. "@{fg highlight}  text()  @{fg text}" becomes "@{fg highlight}text@{fg text}".@{par}

Whenever there is a "@{fg highlight}/*@{fg text}", a "@{fg highlight}*/@{fg text}" or a "@{fg highlight}//@{fg text}" within your text (also not
including all first and last quotes), you will get a warning. These are
HotHelp commands for building context and line-oriented comments. If you
don't want them to become invisible in your final HotHelp project, you
should change your HotHelpComp settings.@{par}
The warning can be suppressed using the -nw switch at the AG2HH command
line.@{par}

All commands will be treated as case-insensitive (except "@{fg highlight}\@$VER:@{fg text}").
This means that, for example, "@{fg highlight}\@endnode@{fg text}" is equal to "@{fg highlight}\@EndNode@{fg text}".@{par}


  @{b}@{u}Commands@{uu}@{ub}@{par}

This section describes the @{amigaguide} commands and how they are handled by
AG2HH.@{par}


@{b}\@node <name> [<title>]@{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@dnode <name> [<title>]@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    These both lines will get converted into invisible keys:@{lindent 0}@{par}
        @{fg highlight}|U-SCHL|<name>|U-SCHL|@{fg text}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    Note that the special entry name "Main" (case-insensitive) will become@{lindent 0}@{par}
        @{fg highlight}|U-SCHL|Startseite|U-SCHL|@{fg text}@{par}


@{b}\@endnode@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    This line gets converted to an end-of-entry marker:@{lindent 0}@{par}
        @{fg highlight}-*-*-*-*-*-@{fg text}@{par}


@{b}\@rem <remark>@{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@remark <remark>@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    This one-line remark will be converted into this:@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 8}        @{fg highlight}// <remark>@{fg text}@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{b}\@{<label> link <node> [<line>]}@{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@{<label> alink <node> [<line>]}@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    These two commands will be converted into references:@{lindent 0}@{par}
        @{fg highlight}|QV|<label>|QV|@{fg text}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    As you can see, the visible button label is used to create a reference.
This way, you don't have to modify your reference labels.@{par}

It is recommended that you use the -ak parameter.@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{settabs 25 50}@{b}\@{b}@{ub}@{tab}@{b}\@{i}@{ub}@{tab}@{b}\@{u}@{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@{ub}@{ub}@{tab}@{b}\@{ui}@{ub}@{tab}@{b}\@{uu}@{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@{plain}@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    These commands will be converted into their corresponding style commands
("@{fg highlight}|SCHR-1|@{fg text}" through "@{fg highlight}|SCHR-8|@{fg text}").@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{b}\@{amigaguide}@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    This command will be converted into the following text:@{lindent 0}@{par}
        @{b}@{fg highlight}AmigaGuideÛ@{fg text} @{ub}@{par}
@{lindent 4}    (including the bold style)@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{b}\@{par}@{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@{line}@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    This will be converted into:@{lindent 0}@{par}
        @{fg highlight}|ABS|@{fg text}@{par}


@{b}\@{body}@{ub}@{par}
@{b}\@{code}@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    These will be converted into:@{lindent 0}@{par}
        @{fg highlight}|FL|@{fg text}@{par}


@{b}\@{lindent <width>}@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    A line containing this command will not be modified, but all following
lines will be indented by <width> spaces.@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{b}\@{tab}@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    A TAB character (ASCII code 9) will be output.@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{b}\@image <filename>@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    This will be converted into:@{lindent 0}@{par}
        @{fg highlight}|GRAF|<filename>@{fg text}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    You must switch image mode on in order to use this one (@{"parameter" link "Usage"} -i).@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{b}All other unknown commands are simply filtered out.@{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "Preferences" "Preferences"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}Preferences@{uu}@{ub}@{par}

Since version 1.1, AG2HH is able to import standard HotHelpCompiler.Pref as
they are created by HotHelpComp.@{par}

If you do not specify the -p @{"parameter" link "Usage"} on the command line, AG2HH will use
the default HotHelpComp preferences as they are shipped with the HotHelp
system from Maxon.@{par}

@endnode
@node "Warnings" "Warnings"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}Warnings@{uu}@{ub}@{par}

Please note that you can switch off all warnings using the -nw or the -q
@{"switches" link "Usage"}.@{par}


@{b}Empty entry label@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    After stripping away all illegal characters from an entry label, the
entry label is illegally empty.@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{b}Illegal entry label@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    After stripping away all illegal characters from an entry label, the
entry label illegally starts with one of the characters "@{fg highlight}0@{fg text}"-"@{fg highlight}9@{fg text}".@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{b}Empty reference label@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    After stripping away all illegal characters from a reference label, the
reference label is illegally empty.@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{b}Illegal reference label@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    After stripping away all illegal characters from a reference label, the
reference label illegally starts with one of the characters "@{fg highlight}0@{fg text}"-"@{fg highlight}9@{fg text}".@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{b}Possible // comment error@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    A "@{fg highlight}//@{fg text}" sequence was found inside the input file. If you didn't change
your preferences, this could introduce unwanted comments in the output
file.@{par}

Note: This warning will not appear if you use the -p parameter!@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{b}Possible /* */ comment error@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    A "@{fg highlight}/*@{fg text}" or "@{fg highlight}*/@{fg text}" sequence was found inside the input file. If you didn't
change your preferences, this could introduce unwanted comments in the
output file.@{par}

Note: This warning will not appear if you use the -p parameter!@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{b}Comment found and converted@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 4}    A "@{fg highlight}\@remark@{fg text}" or "@{fg highlight}\@rem@{fg text}" sequence was found inside the input file and was
converted to a "@{fg highlight}//@{fg text}" sequence.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@endnode

@node "History" "History"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}History@{uu}@{ub}@{par}

1.0, 24-Mar-1997:@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - first version of AG2HH@{lindent 0}@{par}

1.1, 26-Mar-1997:@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - AG2HH is now able to @{"import standard HotHelpCompiler.Pref" link "Preferences"} files as
they are created by HotHelpComp@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - entry names and references labels will now be cut to fit into the size of 49
characters instead of 50 (there's a bug in the HotHelp docs...)@{lindent 0}@{par}


2.0, 01-Apr-1997:@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - lexical scanner completely reworked; does now recognize "\\ fake
@{"commands" link "Commands"}"; unknown commands are simply filtered out@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - implemented new @{"warnings" link "Warnings"}@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - TABs are no longer allowed in entry names and reference labels@{lindent 0}@{par}

2.1, 04-Apr-1997:@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - new @{"AutoKeysÛ mode" link "Usage"}!@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - new @{"AutoDoc mode" link "Usage"}@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - converts \@{lindent ...} and \@{tab}, too@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - \@{line} will now be treated as \@{par}@{lindent 0}@{par}

2.2, 22-Apr-1997:@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - new @{"MUI mode" link "Usage"}@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - improved AutoDoc mode@{lindent 0}@{par}

2.3, 05-Aug-1997:@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - more efficient memory handling implemented, especially in AutoKeysÛ mode@{lindent 0}@{par}

2.4, 26-Aug-1997:@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - implemented @{"AutoSpacesÛ mode" link "Usage"}@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - @{"@image commands" link "Usage"} are also converted now (if you want to)@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - all TABs and ASCII 160 characters will now be converted to normal spaces
(ASCII 32) before anything further is done@{lindent 0}@{par}

@endnode

